 <p><img
        src="http://www3.sympatico.ca/icebreaker/ice1.jpg"
        >
        </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uwendolynkeplegrobal.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Wendolyn KeplegrobAL</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.wired-cafe.com/images/wendhead.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/7/01 9:56:24 am)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.wired-cafe.com/images/wendside.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Changes to what we are proposing to Evade +more.</span><hr size=1> Another problem that I see is that the rogue population is very diverse.  We are all different levels and we all have different agendas.  The evade skill cannot be tailored to accommodate every purpose a rogue will encounter.  Or can it?  For example, I don't xp anymore.  I don't think I have been in an xp group since July of 2000.  My views are very raid oriented as a result.  Another rogue... say in the level 30 to 40 range, is VERY xp group oriented, and most likely has little familiarity with large scale raids.  While we both play the same class, the environment is completely different, and game mechanics which are not present for one, are present for the other.  For rogues at level 60, if you fail to evade or somehow lower your aggro vs. a level 65 mob, you die.  At level 35, if you fail to evade vs. the level 30 mobs you are xping on, you just end up using a lot of the cleric's mana.  The importance of evade is directly proportional to your level.<br>
<br>
That is why I agree a randomness needs to be incorporated into evade.  Like people have mentioned, taking off a fixed % of your total aggro might be too powerful especially near the end of a fight (although I beg to differ with how fast I end up aggro again after a successful evade).  Keeping us #2 or #3 on the list (which moves us up to #1 a second later) is the opposite extreme.  The random placement method provides a chance for the rogue to die the next round because they only dropped down a few slots, or to keep hammering away with backstabs and constant autoattack because they are near the bottom of the list.  Either way, the rogue will NOT know where they are on the list, which can be a good thing.  1st it makes life a little more interesting... requiring us to stay on our toes and watch for that aggro which could be right around the corner.  2nd it provides variability to rogue damage.  Currently, a rogue's level of aggro determines how much damage he/she can do in combat.  If a mob is attacking me, I'm obviously not backstabbing, and almost 100% of the time I have autoattack off until I am dead, or I evade/lower aggro.  Some battles we will need to back off because the random numbers for evade just aren't high enough.  Other battles we might do the same damage we do now.  But every battle would be an adventure...<br>
